Indonesia Stocks: Aneka Tambang, Bakrie Sumatera, Medco Energi

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-04-12T09:18:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-12/indonesia-stocks-aneka-tambang-bakrie-sumatera-medco-energi.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  declined 26.61 points, or 0.7
percent, to 3,719.23, falling for the first time in five days.  Energy companies: PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ),
Indonesia’s biggest listed oil company, slipped 1.8 percent to
2,800 rupiah. PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ), the second
largest, retreated 2.3 percent to 126 rupiah.  Crude oil for May delivery declined 2.5 percent to $109.92
a barrel in  New York  yesterday, the sharpest drop since March
15. The contract slid 0.3 percent to $109.65 in after-hours
trading.  Palm oil makers: PT Perusahaan Perkebunan  London  Sumatra
Indonesia (LSIP IJ), the second-biggest plantation stock by
market value, lost 3.1 percent to 2,350 rupiah. PT Bakrie
Sumatera Plantations (UNSP IJ) fell 1.4 percent to 355 rupiah.  Palm oil  may drop to less than 3,000 ringgit ($991) a
metric ton as output expands, before prices rally on growing use
of soybean oil in U.S. biodiesel,  Dorab Mistry , director of
Godrej International Ltd., said. Futures fell as much as 2.1
percent to 3,345 ringgit a ton in Kuala Lumpur today.  PT Aneka Tambang (ANTM IJ), an Indonesian nickel and gold
producer, declined 1 percent to 2,375 rupiah, the first drop in
five days. Nickel for three-month delivery fell as much as 1.5
percent to $27,300 a metric ton in London. Gold for immediate
delivery fell from a record, losing 0.4 percent to $1,456.78 an
ounce.  PT Indofood Sukses Makmur (INDF IJ), which owns  Indonesia ’s
biggest instant-noodle maker, rose 1 percent to 5,400 rupiah,
providing the biggest support to the benchmark  stock index .
Wheat futures fell from a six-week high in Chicago yesterday,
reducing the risk of higher production costs. Indofood uses
wheat to make instant noodles.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Reinie Booysen at   rbooysen@bloomberg.net . 